BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Our goal is to remove that [`-7.3`] from the left side. Since that negative number is being _added_ to [`z\text{,}`] we could _subtract_ [`-7.3`] from both sides.

[```\newcommand{\subtractright}[1]{{\highlight{{{}-#1}}}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
-7.3+z\amp=5.1\\
-7.3+z\subtractright{(-7.3)}\amp=5.1\subtractright{(-7.3)}\\
z\amp=12.4
\end{aligned}
```]

It is just as effective to add positive [`7.3`] to each side.

[```\newcommand{\addright}[1]{{\highlight{{{}+#1}}}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
-7.3+z\amp=5.1\\
-7.3+z\addright{7.3}\amp=5.1\addright{7.3}\\
z\amp=12.4
\end{aligned}
```]

We should check the solution by substituting [`12.4`] in for [`z`] in the original equation:

[```\newcommand{\substitute}[1]{{\color{blue}{{#1}}}}\newcommand{\confirm}[1]{\stackrel{\checkmark}{#1}}\newcommand{\wonder}[1]{\stackrel{\text{?}}{#1}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
-7.3+z\amp=5.1\\
-7.3+(\substitute{12.4})\amp\wonder{=}5.1\\
5.1\amp\confirm{=}5.1
\end{aligned}
```]

The solution [`12.4`] is checked, and the solution set is [`\{12.4\}\text{.}`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

